[normal]te differe
[normal]nt in the Cambrian most of  
[normal]the ancient
[normal] continental masses were drowned and fringed by massive carbonate platforms.  Min
[normal]imum estimates of the
[normal] carbon sequestered during the Cambrian yield 1,396,000,000,000,000 tonnes or 1,396, 000 
[normal]gigatonnes
[normal].  It 
[normal]is not possible to reconcile the very high atmospheric CO2 levels during the Palaeozoic, some  
[normal]15 – 17 times current  levels (5800 – 6500 
[normal]ppmv
[normal]) with the IPPC projections for doubling of CO2 (385 – 770ppmv),  especially given the complete lack of evidence o
[normal]f any adverse conditions in the oceans ( 
[normal]Veizer
[normal] et al 1999) or on land, as evidenced by evolution of land plants in the Devonian.
