[normal]13[bold])[bold].[bold]The worst aspect of the IPCC report is their total disregard of the solar influence on climate.  In the very period where they are 95% confident of human influence we have 
[normal]the most active solar cycles of the 20[bold]th[bold] Century showing solar maxima 30 to 40% gr[bold]eater than the 19[bold]th[bold] Century or the first half of the 20th.[bold] [bold]   From 1950 there are six cycles numbered 
[normal]19[bold] to 
[normal]24[bold].  The daily sun spot maximum at cycle 
[normal]19[bold] was 
[normal]200[bold] dropping to 
[normal]110[bold] in cycle 
[normal]20[bold].  Cycle 
[normal]21[bold] showed an increase to 
[normal]163[bold] then there is gradual decrease through cycles 
[normal]22[bold] and 
[normal]23[bold] from 
[normal]155[bold] to 
[normal]115[bold] and finally cycle
[normal] 24[bold] 
[normal]is at a low of 
[normal]65[bold].  This pattern of solar variability has a 95% correlation with global average temperature and so there is no need to search for missing heat.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Fig.2 Illustrates the Solar Sun Spot cycle from 1950 
[normal]–
[normal] 2013
[normal], (cycles 19 – 24), 19 on the left, and showing a significant decline in activity especially since 1997.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]14[bold])[bold] The decline in solar activity through the last Sun Spot Cycles (Nos. 21, 22, 23 an
[normal]d 24) is shown in Fig.2, and this is consistent with the lack of warming in the last 15 years.  A weakening C
[normal]ycle 23
[normal] lasted for 12.4 years and
[normal] recorded 821 sun spot free days, a number not seen since the 19th Century.
[normal]  The strong decline in sunspot number 
[normal]in Cycle24 suggests that we are now entering a solar minimum indicating the probability of cooling in the next decade.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]15). [bold]There is considerably more evidence both observational and experimental which confirms the Sun’s role in determining climate.  
[normal]Henr
[normal]ik
[normal] 
[normal]Svensmark
[normal] has been a leading proponent of the solar influence on climate and in 1998 published an article to show that
[normal] Earth's temperature follows more close
[normal]ly decadal
[normal] variations in galactic cosmic ray flux and solar cycle length, than other solar activ
[normal]ity 
[normal]parameters.  He then demonstrated a close relationship between cosmic ray flux and the development of low cloud (Marsh and 
[normal]Svensmark
[normal] 2000)    
[normal]Svensmark
[normal] then demonstrated in his laboratory (The SKY study) that incoming cosmic rays entering a simulated a
[normal]tmosphere caused  the
[normal] growth of clusters of molecules of the kind that build cloud condensation nuclei. These are specks of sulphuric ac
[normal]id on which cloud droplets form.(
[normal]Svensmark
[normal] et al 2007) 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1[bold]6[bold]).   In order to confirm these observations that more fully met the constraints of the atmosphere and the nature of cosmic particles a much more sophisticated experiment was undertaken at the European Organization for Nuclear Research (CERN).  The results,
[normal] released in 2011, have fully substantiated 
[normal]Svensmark’s
[normal] hypothesis that incoming cosmic ray flux produces a steady production of new ionized particles (molecular clusters) that induce the nucleation of clouds.  (Kirby et al Nature 2011),  Therefore, in an 
[normal]exceptional demonstration of Scientific Method in climate science through observation, measurement and experiment 
[normal]Svensmark
[normal] has shown that the Earth’s Climate results
[normal] in large part
[normal] from an interplay of the Sun’s activity and the incoming flux of cosmic ray
[normal]s from space, primarily the 
[normal]Milky Way Galaxy.   When the solar flux
[normal] is weak cosmic bombardment is strong and low cloud is propagated causing 
[normal]cooling; with an active Sun, 
[normal]as we have had for most of the last Century
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]the increased solar flux deflects and red
[normal]uces the 
[normal]cosmic
[normal] ray
[normal] influx
[normal]. The weaker cosmic ray flux results in less cloud and a 
[normal]warmer climate.  This hypothesis explains in detail the climatic history of the Earth for the last 550 million years w
[normal]ithout resort to CO2 forcing.
[normal]The failure of IPCC to ac
[normal]knowledge this groundbreaking research on 
[normal]cosmoclimatology
[normal] is entirely political and without scientific merit.
